close_symbols: OS_printf (function) — referenced/used by OS_CHECK_POINTER in some builds
UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType (function/macro) — possible unit-test stub helper invoked by OS_CHECK_POINTER in the build graph
explanation: To determine whether OS_CondVarGetIdByName modifies any of its parameters (which would violate the MISRA rule), the analysis must include: (1) the exact definition/expansion of OS_CHECK_POINTER because it is invoked in the function body — a macro expansion could reassign the pointer parameters or perform other modifications; (2) any symbols that the OS_CHECK_POINTER expansion calls (OS_printf and the UT_* stub helpers shown in the static call graph) so you can see whether the macro expansion or those helpers mutate the parameter variables; (3) the prototype/definition of OS_ObjectIdFindByName to confirm its parameter types (e.g., whether it receives osal_id_t * or osal_id_t **), because if the callee were declared to take a pointer-to-pointer it could indicate a different usage pattern (even though modifications inside the callee to its own parameter variable do not count as modifying the caller's parameter, the declaration clarifies intent and whether the address-of operator is being used); and (4) the typedefs for osal_id_t and int32 so the analyzer knows the parameter types and can correctly reason about pointer vs object modification. Together these symbols let the next analyzer verify that no assignment to the formal parameters (var_id or var_name) occurs in the macro expansion or the function body.
